Creating a function to convert Markdown to HTML in C++ involves parsing the Markdown syntax and replacing it with the corresponding HTML tags. Below is an example of a simple function that performs this conversion. This function is not complete and does not cover all Markdown syntax, but it should serve as a starting point.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <map>

// Define a map to store the conversion rules
std::map<char, std::string> markdownToHtmlMap = {
    {'#', "<h1>"},
    {'*', "<ul><li>"},
    {'`', "<code>"},
    {'[', "<a href=\""},
    {'(', "\">"},
    {']', "</a>"},
    {')', ""}
};

// Function to convert Markdown to HTML
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Replace each character in the map with its HTML counterpart
    for (const auto& pair : markdownToHtmlMap) {
        markdown.replace(pair.first, 1, pair.second);
    }

    // Remove leading and trailing spaces
    markdown.erase(std::remove(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), ' '), markdown.end());
    markdown.erase(0, std::find_if(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), std::not1(std::ptr_fun<int, int>(std::isspace))));
    markdown.erase(std::find_if(markdown.rbegin(), markdown.rend(), std::not1(std::ptr_fun<int, int>(std::isspace))).base(), markdown.end());

    // Return the converted HTML string
    return markdown;
}

int main() {
    // Example Markdown string
    std::string markdown = "# This is a header\n"
                           "* This is a list item\n"
                           "`This is code`";

    // Convert to HTML
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);

    // Output the HTML string
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This function uses a `std::map` to store the conversion rules, which are simple replacements for now. It replaces each character in the map with its corresponding HTML tag or attribute. The function also removes leading and trailing spaces to clean up the output.

Please note that this is a very basic example and does not cover all Markdown syntax, such as lists, blockquotes, tables, and footnotes. Implementing a full Markdown parser in C++ is a complex task and may require the use of a library or a more sophisticated parsing algorithm.

Also, this function does not handle nested elements or preserve the structure of the Markdown document. For a more robust conversion, you would need to write a more sophisticated parser that can handle these cases.

